 Aboriginal people's participation in the courts rather than on narrow categories such as "the state" and "the accused," Gavigan allows Aboriginal defendants, witnesses, and informants to emerge in vivid detail and tell the story in their own terms. Their experiences stand as evidence that the criminal law and the Indian Act operated in complex and contradictory ways that included both the mediation and the enforcement of relations of inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminal courtszSaskatchewanxHistory. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzSaskatchewanxHistory. 0aCriminal lawzSaskatchewanxHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCriminal justice systemzSaskatchewanxHistory. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482254140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774822541423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774822541/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles